1. INTRODUCTION: THE QUANTUM IMPERATIVE

1.1 The End of Classical Encryption

The advent of quantum computing presents both unprecedented opportunity and existential threat to global communications. Shor's algorithm, when run on sufficiently large quantum computers, can break RSA-2048 encryption in hours rather than millennia. Current estimates suggest cryptographically-relevant quantum computers (CRQCs) will exist by 2030-2035, rendering today's secure communications fundamentally vulnerable.

The Vulnerability Timeline:

· 2024-2028: Harvest-now-decrypt-later attacks begin - data encrypted today will be decryptable
· 2029-2033: First specialized quantum computers break 1024-bit encryption
· 2034-2038: General-purpose quantum computers break 2048-bit encryption
· 2039+: All classical public-key infrastructure becomes obsolete

1.2 Limitations of Current Infrastructure

5G and fiber networks suffer from fundamental limitations:

· Security: Based on mathematical complexity, not physical laws
· Latency: Speed-of-light limitations in fiber (200km/ms)
· Coverage: 47% of world population lacks internet access; oceans, poles, and remote areas uncovered
· Capacity: Shannon limit constrains spectral efficiency
· Resilience: Centralized infrastructure vulnerable to natural disasters and targeted attacks

1.3 The Quantum Alternative

Quantum communication offers advantages rooted in physics:

· Information-Theoretic Security: Based on no-cloning theorem and measurement disturbance
· Lower Latency: Quantum teleportation enables protocol-level advantages
· Novel Capabilities: Distributed quantum computing, enhanced sensing, quantum internet
· Physical Resilience: Satellite-based systems immune to ground-based disruptions

---

2. VISION AND ARCHITECTURAL PRINCIPLES

2.1 Core Vision

To create a global quantum communication network that provides unconditional security, enables distributed quantum computing, and serves as foundational infrastructure for the 21st century digital economy.

2.2 Architectural Principles

1. Quantum-First Design: Quantum protocols as primary, classical as fallback
2. Infrastructure Independence: Minimal reliance on existing telecom infrastructure
3. Global Equity: Coverage including oceans, poles, and developing regions
4. Forward Security: Designed for post-quantum era from inception
5. Graceful Degradation: Quantum failure modes revert to best-available classical
6. Open Standards: Interoperable protocols to avoid vendor lock-in

2.3 Technical Goals

Metric Target Current Best (Lab) Improvement
Entanglement Distribution Rate 10⁶ pairs/sec over 1000km 10³ pairs/sec over 100km 1000×
Quantum Memory Coherence 1 second 1 minute (at cryogenic) 60×
Daytime Operation 50% of nighttime rate 0.1% (with filtering) 500×
End-to-End Latency <1ms (continental) ~10ms (fiber) 10×
Network Availability 99.999% 99.9% (best fiber) 10× improvement
Security Level Information-theoretic Computational (128-bit) ∞ improvement

