3. QUANTUM PHYSICAL LAYER

3.1 Entanglement Generation and Distribution

3.1.1 Satellite-Based Entanglement Sources

```
Technology: Waveguide-integrated spontaneous parametric down-conversion (SPDC)
├─ Material: Periodically poled lithium niobate (PPLN) with quantum dot enhancement
├─ Wavelength: 1550.12nm (C-band for atmospheric transparency)
├─ Pair Generation Rate: 10⁹ pairs/second at 50mW pump
├─ Entanglement Fidelity: >0.98 (Bell state measurement)
├─ Spectral Purity: <100MHz bandwidth (0.8pm at 1550nm)
└─ Space Qualification: Radiation-hardened, thermal-stabilized ±0.01°C
```

3.1.2 Quantum Memories for Repeaters

Three complementary technologies for different network segments:

```
1. Atomic Vapor Cells (for satellite repeaters)
   ├─ Species: Rubidium-87 with buffer gas
   ├─ Storage Time: 1ms (goal: 10ms with spin echo)
   ├─ Efficiency: >50% (write/read)
   ├─ Bandwidth: 10MHz
   └─ Operating Temp: 65°C ± 0.1°C

2. Rare-Earth Doped Crystals (for ground stations)
   ├─ Material: Europium:Y₂SiO₅
   ├─ Storage Time: 6 hours (at 2K)
   ├─ Efficiency: >50%
   ├─ Multimode Capacity: 100 temporal modes
   └─ Requirement: Cryogenic cooling (2-4K)

3. Diamond NV Centers (for portable units)
   ├─ Storage Time: 1ms at room temperature
   ├─ Efficiency: <10% (current), >30% (goal)
   ├─ Integration: Chip-scale with photonics
   └─ Advantage: Room temperature operation
```

3.2 Single-Photon Detection

```
Superconducting Nanowire Single-Photon Detectors (SNSPD):
├─ Material: NbN or WS₂ (2D material alternative)
├─ Active Area: 20×20μm
├─ Detection Efficiency: >90% at 1550nm
├─ Dark Count Rate: <1 count/second
├─ Timing Jitter: <20ps FWHM
├─ Recovery Time: <10ns
├─ Operating Temperature: 2.8K (closed-cycle cryocooler)
├─ Space Qualification: Survives launch vibration, radiation
└─ Production Cost: <$10,000 at scale (currently >$50,000)

Alternative Technology: Single-Photon Avalanche Diodes (SPADs)
├─ Advantage: Room temperature operation
├─ Disadvantage: Lower efficiency (~70%), higher noise
├─ Application: Short-range, cost-sensitive nodes
└─ Roadmap: 90% efficiency by 2030 with meta-surface enhancement
```

3.3 Atmospheric Channel Management

3.3.1 Adaptive Quantum Optics

Atmospheric turbulence presents unique challenges for quantum states:

```
Problems:
1. Phase scrambling: Destroys coherence of photonic qubits
2. Intensity fluctuations (scintillation): Varies detection probability
3. Beam wander: Loss of alignment
4. Polarization changes: Affects encoding basis

Solutions:
├─ Wavefront Correction: 1000-actuator deformable mirrors, 2kHz update
├─ Spatial Diversity: Multiple transmitter apertures
├─ Temporal Diversity: Pulse position modulation
├─ Quantum State Tomography Feedback: Real-time characterization and compensation
└─ Predictive Correction: Machine learning based on atmospheric models
```

3.3.2 Daytime Operation

Sunlight background (~10¹⁸ photons/m²/s) threatens single-photon detection:

```
Mitigation Strategy (Combined achieves >10¹⁰ background suppression):
1. Spectral Filtering: 0.01nm bandwidth atomic line filters (Rb or K)
2. Spatial Filtering: Single-mode fiber coupling (10μrad field of view)
3. Temporal Filtering: 100ps gates synchronized to 10ps
4. Polarization Filtering: 10⁶:1 extinction ratio
5. Coincidence Detection: Requires multiple detectors (reduces rate but enables daytime)

Performance Target: 
Night: 10⁵ pairs/second at 1000km
Day: 10³ pairs/second (1% of night rate, usable for key distribution)
```

