4. SATELLITE CONSTELLATION ARCHITECTURE

4.1 Three-Layer Orbital Architecture

```
Layer 1: Quantum Source Satellites (216 satellites)
├─ Altitude: 600km Sun-synchronous orbit
├─ Function: Primary entanglement generation
├─ Payload: Entangled photon source, coarse pointing
├─ Crosslinks: Optical to adjacent layer 1 satellites
├─ Downlinks: Quantum channels to ground
└─ Design Life: 5 years

Layer 2: Quantum Repeater Satellites (96 satellites)
├─ Altitude: 800km inclined orbit (45°)
├─ Function: Entanglement swapping and routing
├─ Payload: Quantum memory, Bell state measurement
├─ Crosslinks: 4 optical terminals (up/down/left/right)
├─ Memory Time: 1ms (enables swapping over 240km)
└─ Key Innovation: All-optical processing where possible

Layer 3: User Access Satellites (288 satellites)
├─ Altitude: 1200km Walker constellation (55°)
├─ Function: User connectivity and service delivery
├─ Payload: Classical-quantum interface, user beam forming
├─ Uplinks: From user terminals (ground, ship, air)
├─ Downlinks: To users with beam-steered arrays
└─ Capacity: 10,000 simultaneous user connections

Total: 600 active satellites + 60 orbital spares
```

4.2 Satellite Design Specifications

4.2.1 Quantum Source Satellite (QSS-1)

```
Bus Specifications:
├─ Mass: 350kg (150kg payload, 200kg bus)
├─ Dimensions: 2.0×1.5×1.0m stowed
├─ Power: 800W peak (solar arrays 6m² GaAs, 35% efficient)
├─ Propulsion: Hall-effect thrusters (80mN, Isp=1500s)
├─ Attitude Control: 0.01° accuracy, 0.001°/s stability
├─ Communication: 
   ├─ S-band: 1Mbps TT&C
   ├─ X-band: 100Mbps science data
   ├─ Optical crosslink: 10Gbps to adjacent satellites
└─ Design Life: 5 years (10-year goal)

Payload Specifications:
├─ Entangled Photon Source:
   ├─ Type: Waveguide PPLN with quantum dots
   ├─ Rate: 10⁹ pairs/second at 50mW pump
   ├─ Wavelength: 1550nm ± 0.1nm
   ├─ Redundancy: 3 independent sources
   └─ Lifetime: >10¹⁵ pairs (5 years at 10⁷ pairs/second)

├─ Fine Pointing System:
   ├─ Telescope: 150mm off-axis Cassegrain
   ├─ Pointing Accuracy: 0.5μrad RMS
   ├─ Beam Divergence: 10μrad (diffraction limited)
   ├─ Acquisition Time: <5 seconds
   └─ Handover: <100ms between ground stations

├─ Quantum Memory (for future upgrades):
   └─ Initial: Simple delay lines
   └─ Upgrade: Atomic vapor cells (1ms storage)

└─ Classical Beacon:
   ├─ Wavelength: 976nm (eye-safe, low background)
   ├─ Power: 500mW for acquisition and tracking
   └─ Modulation: 10kHz for range finding
```

4.2.2 Manufacturing at Scale

```
Production Facility Requirements:
├─ Location: Neutral territory with export control flexibility
├─ Cleanroom: 5000m² ISO Class 4-6
├─ Workforce: 500 engineers and technicians
├─ Automation: 70% robotic assembly
├─ Testing: 
   ├─ Thermal vacuum: -80°C to +150°C, 10⁻⁶ Torr
   ├─ Vibration: 14.1Grms random, 20-2000Hz
   ├─ Radiation: 30krad(Si) total dose
   └─ Lifetime: 1000-hour burn-in for each satellite
└─ Production Rate: 2 satellites/week at full capacity

Cost Reduction Strategy:
├─ Bus: Modified Starlink bus ($500k in quantity)
├─ Payload: Photonic integration reduces assembly cost
├─ Launch: Rideshare on Starship ($5M per satellite)
├─ Operations: Autonomous with minimal ground intervention
└─ Target Cost: $25M per satellite at 100+ quantity
```

4.3 Launch and Deployment Strategy

```
Launch Vehicles:
Primary: SpaceX Starship
├─ Capacity: 100+ satellites per launch (150t to LEO)
├─ Cost: ~$50M per launch ($500k per satellite)
├─ Launch Rate: 6 per year during deployment
